import numpy as np 

from plotnine import (
    ggplot, 
    aes, 
    geom_point,
    scale_x_continuous,
    scale_y_continuous,
    labs,
    theme,
    scale_fill_manual,
    scale_size,
    annotate,
    element_line

)
# 3. Recreate graph
( 
    ggplot(df, aes("income", "life_exp", size = "population"))
    + geom_point(aes(fill="four_regions"),
    color="black",
    stroke=0.3)
+ scale_x_continuous(
    trans = 'log2',
    breaks = [500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000],
    labels = ["500", "1000", "2000", "4000", "8000", "16k", "32k", "64k"])
+ scale_y_continuous(
    limits=(20, 90),
    breaks=range(20, 91, 10))
+ labs(
    x = "Income", 
    y="Life Expectancy")
+ theme(
    figure_size=(10,4),
    panel_grid_major=element_line(color="black", size=0.6, alpha=0.4),
    panel_grid_minor=None)
+ scale_size(range=(0.6,25))
+ annotate("text", x=8000, y=50, label="2010", size= 130, color = "black", alpha = 0.3)


)

# 4. Different Geometry than geom_point (used chatgpt for help)

from plotnine import geom_violin

    ggplot(df, aes(x="four_regions", y="life_exp", fill="four_regions"))
    + geom_violin(trim=False)  # trim=False shows full tails of the distribution
    + labs(
        x="Region",
        y="Life Expectancy"
    )
    + theme(
        figure_size=(8, 5),
        panel_grid_major=element_line(color="black", size=0.4, alpha=0.3),
        panel_grid_minor=None
    )

df2['exports'] = pd.to_numeric(df2['exports'], errors ='coerce')
df2['imports'] = pd.to_numeric(df2['imports'], errors ='coerce')
df2['energy'] = pd.to_numeric(df2['energy'], errors ='coerce')
# 3. Recreate the Graph 
( 
    ggplot(df2, aes('exports', 'imports', size = 'energy'))
    + geom_point(aes(fill="four_regions"),
    color="black",
    stroke=0.3
    )
+ scale_x_continuous(
    limits = (0, 220),
    breaks = range(0, 241, 20),
    labels = [str(x) for x in range (0, 241, 20)]
    )
+ scale_y_continuous(
    limits= (0, 400),
    breaks=range(0, 401, 50)
    )
+ labs(
    x = "Exports (\% of GDP)", 
    y="Imports (\% of GDP)"
    )
+ theme(
    figure_size=(10,4),
    panel_grid_major=element_line(color="black", size=0.6, alpha=0.4),
    panel_grid_minor=None)
+ scale_size(range = (0.6, 22))
+ annotate("text", x = 110, y = 150, label = "1997", size = 170, color = "black", alpha = 0.3 )
)

# 4. Different Graph (used Chatgpt for help)

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, labs

(
    ggplot(df2, aes(x="exports", y="imports", color="four_regions"))
    + geom_point(alpha=0.7)
    + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=False)   # linear regression lines
    + labs(x="Exports (% of GDP)", y="Imports (% of GDP)", title="Imports vs Exports with Trends")
)

df3['internet_users'] = pd.to_numeric(df3['internet_users'], errors ='coerce')
df3['income'] = pd.to_numeric(df3['income'], errors ='coerce')
# 3. Recreate the Graph 
( 
    ggplot(df3, aes('internet_users', 'gdp', size = 'income'))
    + geom_point(aes(fill="four_regions"),
    color="black",
    stroke=0.3
    )
+ scale_x_continuous(
    limits = (0, 90),
    breaks = range(0, 91, 10),
    labels = [str(x) for x in range (0, 91, 10)]
    )
+ scale_y_continuous(
    trans = 'log2',
    breaks = [200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000, 20000, 50000, 100000],
    labels = ["200", "500", "1000", "2000", "5000", "10k", "20k", "50k", "100k"])
   
+ labs(
    x = "Individuals using the Internet", 
    y = "GDP/capita"
    )
+ theme(
    figure_size=(10,4),
    panel_grid_major=element_line(color="black", size=0.6, alpha=0.4),
    panel_grid_minor=None)
+ scale_size(range = (0.5, 20))
+ annotate("text", x = 50, y = 6000, label = "2 0 0 1", size = 130, color = "black", alpha = 0.2 )
)
